ris accord passed a threshold on Oct. 5 of 55 nations accounting for more than 55 percent of greenhouse gas emissions, allowing it to come into force 30 days later.', u'Ratification was swift compared to other international treaties, showing strong international support, but around 100 countries have yet to ratify it.', u'"This is a moment to celebrate. It is also a moment to look ahead with sober assessment and renewed will over the task ahead," United Nations\' climate chief Patricia Espinosa said in a statement.', u'"In a short time \u2013 and certainly in the next 15 years \u2013 we need to see unprecedented reductions in greenhouse gas emissions and unequalled efforts to build societies that can resist rising climate impacts," she said.', u'The Paris Agreement seeks to wean the world economy off fossil fuels in the second half of the century, limiting the rise in average world temperatures to "well below" 2.0 degrees Celsius (3.6 Fahrenheit) above preindustrial times.', u'It also notes an ambition to limiting temperature rise even further to 1.5 degrees.', u'The pact kicked off a rolling start in the Pacific region on Thursday, home to low-lying islands states which are in danger of rising sea levels.', u"On the same day, the annual report of U.N. Environment analyzed countries' current pledges for emission cuts and said they were not sufficient.", u'Even if emission-cutting pledges under the Paris agreement are fully implemented, predicted 2030 emissions could put the world on track for a temperature rise of 2.9 to 3.4 degrees Celsius this century, the report said.', u'The latest round of U.N. climate talks begin on Monday in Marrakesh, Morocco, where representatives from countries will try to find ways to implement the agreement and work out the rules.', u'Environmental campaign groups, as well as some businesses, investors and academics said the meeting in Marrakesh must keep up the spirit of international support for climate action.', u'"Even with the commitments made in Paris and encouraging action on the ground, we will not meet our aspiration of limiting warming to 1.5 degrees unless we move faster and at the scale that is needed," World Bank Group President Jim Yong Kim said.', u'"As the world heads into (the meeting) in Marrakesh, we must regain the sense of urgency we felt a year ago," he said.', u'Singapore carbon tax would hit refiners, help renewables', u'Also In Global Energy News', u'Also In Global Energy News', u'Also In Global Energy News', u'Next In ', u'Toshiba seeks $8.8 billion for chip unit stake as banks fret over risks', u"TOKYO Japan's Toshiba Corp  wants to raise at least 1 trillion yen ($8.8 billion) by selling most of its flash memory chip business, seeking to create a buffer for any fresh financial problems, a source with direct knowledge of the matter said.", u'Climate doubter Pruitt takes EPA reins as Trump targets regulations', u"WASHINGTON The U.S. Senate confirmed President Donald Trump's pick to run the Environmental Protection Agency on Friday over the objections of Democrats and environmentalists worried he will gut the agency, as the administration readies executive orders to ease regulation on drillers and miners.", u'India still keen to buy Westinghouse reactors despite Toshiba meltdown', u"NEW DELHI India does not expect fallout from the financial meltdown at Toshiba Corp  to halt plans to buy six nuclear reactors from the Japanese company's U.S. nuclear unit Westinghouse, a senior government official told Reuters on Friday.", u'REUTERS', u'Sponsored ', u'Content', u'From Around the ', u'Web', u'Promoted by Revcontent', u'Pictures', u'Photos of the Day', u'Topics', u'X', u'Follow Reuters: ', u'Follow Us On Twitter', u'Follow Us On Facebook', u'Follow Us On RSS', u'Follow Us On Instagram', u'Follow Us On YouTube', u'Follow Us On LinkedIn', u'Subscribe: ', u'Feeds', u'Newsletters', u'Podcasts', u'Apps', u'Reuters News Agency', u'Brand Attribution Guidelines', u'Careers', u'Reuters is